SENATE BILL No. 285
A BILL FOR AN ACT to amend the Indiana Code concerning local
government.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the State of Indiana:
1 SECTION 1. IC 5-20-1-28 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
2 AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY
3 1, 2026]: Sec. 28. (a) The authority shall establish eligibility
4 criteria, in accordance with federal law, for a potential recipient to
5 be included in the authority's application for funding under the
6 federal Continuum of Care program (24 CFR Part 578).
7 (b) On an annual basis and in a manner prescribed by the
8 authority, each recipient of funds distributed by the authority
9 under the federal Continuum of Care program (24 CFR Part 578)
10 shall submit a report to the authority summarizing:
11 (1) information concerning the recipient's efforts to address
12 unsheltered homelessness; and
13 (2) whether the recipient reduced unsheltered homelessness.
14 SECTION 2. IC 10-11-2-36 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
15 AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY
16 1, 2026]: Sec. 36. Not later than July 1 of each year, the state police
17 department shall provide to the Indiana housing and community
SB 285—LS 7097/DI 147

2
1 development authority the information received under
2 IC 36-1-31.5-4.
3 SECTION 3. IC 35-52-36-0.5 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA
4 CODE AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS
5 [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 0.5. IC 36-1-31.5-1 defines a
6 crime concerning the unauthorized use of land owned by the state
7 or a political subdivision to camp, sleep, or use for long term
8 shelter.
9 SECTION 4. IC 36-1-31.5 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
10 AS A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
11 JULY 1, 2026]:
12 Chapter 31.5. Prohibition of Street Camping
13 Sec. 1. (a) A person may not camp, sleep, or use for long term
14 shelter land owned by the state or a political subdivision, unless the
15 land has been authorized for that use by law.
16 (b) If:
17 (1) a person violates subsection (a); and
18 (2) the person has not previously violated subsection (a);
19 the law enforcement officer who discovers the violation shall first
20 give the person a warning and provide the person with information
21 regarding locations authorized by law to provide services or
22 shelter.
23 (c) A person who knowingly or intentionally violates subsection
24 (a) commits street camping, a Class C misdemeanor, if:
25 (1) the person has received a warning under subsection (b);
26 (2) at least forty-eight (48) hours have elapsed since the
27 warning was issued; and
28 (3) the person is camping or sleeping on, or using for long
29 term shelter, land owned by the state or a political subdivision
30 that is located within a three hundred (300) foot radius of the
31 location where the warning under subsection (b) was issued.
32 (d) A person charged with an offense under subsection (c) is
33 eligible to participate in a diversion program, including:
34 (1) a prosecutorial diversion program under IC 33-39-1-8; or
35 (2) a forensic diversion program under IC 11-12-3.7.
36 (e) If a law enforcement officer has reasonable grounds to
37 believe that a person is either dangerous or gravely disabled, and
38 is in immediate need of hospitalization and treatment, an officer
39 may initiate emergency detention procedures under IC 12-26-5.
40 Sec. 2. The court may refer a person charged with an offense
41 under section 1 of this chapter for evaluation and treatment under
42 IC 33-23-18-6.
SB 285—LS 7097/DI 147

